This week, we=E2=80=99re painting our loved ones, eavesdropping on whales, =
sharing confessions, and analyzing lyrics.
ART
Portrait of a marriage
As Alex Belth and his wife manage life with chronic illness, they both find=
 comfort in his portraits of her=E2=80=94dozens created over the course of =
years.
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve Never Been Anyone=E2=80=99s Muse=E2=80=9D [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/e7489b31-f91c-40c9-8b6c-1e13728f707f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ=
29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9ecHmePkbA3ys ]
=E2=80=94Alex Belth  in Dig This with Alex Belth =20
We left the Bronx and moved to a small village in Vermont, grateful to be s=
afe and in less clamorous environs. Emily appreciated the change=E2=80=94an=
d in time, so did I=E2=80=94but her health didn=E2=80=99t miraculously impr=
ove. Her visual system, in particular, continued to decline. Watching TV fo=
r more than a minute made her ill=E2=80=94she had to limit time on the phon=
e, and good luck with that=E2=80=94let alone looking at a computer, or thro=
ugh the windshield of my car.
There=E2=80=99s only so many hours one can listen to podcasts on the couch =
without going mad. So one evening five years ago just before Thanksgiving, =
Em says to me, =E2=80=9CLet=E2=80=99s paint.=E2=80=9D
I smiled. She didn=E2=80=99t like drawing or painting even though her mothe=
r is a fabulous visual artist. (I took Em to the Metropolitan Museum of Art=
 on our first date, thinking I=E2=80=99d impress her with my knowledge of p=
ainting; I talked until I left her limp. And hungry.)
=E2=80=9COf course,=E2=80=9D I said, =E2=80=9Clove to join you.=E2=80=9D
We set ourselves up on the dining room table with acrylics and markers. She=
 made abstract pictures, interrupting herself only to tell me she didn=E2=
=80=99t know what she was doing.
I drew pictures of her.
Em=E2=80=99s artistic career was short-lived. After a few days, the paintin=
g fucked up her vision just like everything else. By that point, I was in a=
 groove. And so during the first long covid winter, I made drawings and pai=
ntings of my wife and it was like seeing her for the first time.
It would take time to knock the rust off my skills, but I wasn=E2=80=99t cr=
ippled by self-doubt and criticism.
There are few pieces of writing I look back on with affection, but I dig my=
 artwork, despite the technical flaws. Experiencing this again was unexpect=
ed, surprising and energizing.
Drawing someone, capturing not so much their likeness but their spirit, is =
the stuff of infatuation; it took on a different energy with someone I=E2=
=80=99d known, and adored, for almost twenty years.
I drew Em as we hung out in the evenings, occasionally asking her to hold s=
till a sec, but just as often working from photographs I=E2=80=99d taken wi=
th my phone. After finishing a picture, which could take minutes or days, I=
 showed it to her, half-eager for her approval while anxious to be free of =
wanting it. (No wonder uncle Fred didn=E2=80=99t fill in facial features=E2=
=80=94they weren=E2=80=99t only difficult to render but tempting to over-wo=
rk.)
Em usually brightened at the sight of them, the colors, the vibe, and liked=
 some and didn=E2=80=99t like others.
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve never been anyone=E2=80=99s muse,=E2=80=9D she said.
I=E2=80=99ve watched her a lot over the years, suffering and in despair. I=
=E2=80=99ve watched her sleep, her features soft and unguarded while I pray=
 for relief. And I=E2=80=99ve watched her doubled over in laughter after ca=
lling me a cheater and a slut for beating her in a game of backgammon.
Over the course of three years I made hundreds of drawings and dozens of pa=
intings of my wife, evoking her many moods=E2=80=94and mine.
We worried about how best to hang all this artwork in the living room. When=
 I asked our landlord for advice, he didn=E2=80=99t warn me about making ho=
les in the walls. Instead, he said: =E2=80=9CPerfection is an offense to th=
e gods!=E2=80=9D
A haphazard gallery of more than 20 picture frames went up=E2=80=9411x8 dra=
wings, 18x24 paintings. Sometimes, I=E2=80=99d be so excited to finish a pa=
inting session just to get the canvas on the wall.
I basked in the luxury of staring at a picture, for hours and days, relieve=
d of the pressure of time=E2=80=94and of scrolling as a way of seeing. Tink=
ering, plotting adjustments.
Meanwhile, Em sat across from me on the other side of the couch listening t=
o a podcast with her earbuds on=E2=80=94true crime, anyone? Or we=E2=80=99d=
 follow a movie on TV, her not looking, me describing the action. She compo=
sed letters, longhand, to a few cherished friends with bright fountain pen =
ink (shimmer, glitter, fuchsia!).
The gallery overwhelmed Emily at first=E2=80=94she=E2=80=99s not one for at=
tention. But that changed as she looked and lived with her many portraits. =
She developed favorites, ones she didn=E2=80=99t want to be removed.
=E2=80=9CWhen I=E2=80=99m feeling down,=E2=80=9D she says, =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=
=99ll look up from the couch and be reminded of the things I do when I feel=
 well: hunting for shark teeth, picking blueberries and flowers, doing yoga=
=E2=80=94even talking to an alpaca.
=E2=80=9CThen I think: Somebody loves me enough to keep looking.=E2=80=9D
