HOLLYWOOD
New Hollywood dreams
Diane Keaton (RIP) keeps sneaking up in this week=E2=80=99s selections: her=
e, Annie Hall is used by Sam Jennings (via Seth Rogen=E2=80=99s character i=
n The Studio) to wonder where the ambitions of New Hollywood have gone.
The New Hollywood Dilemma [ https://substack.com/redirect/1fa3ba8f-2be7-414=
e-b804-a1a764c52149?j=3DeyJ1IjoiMW5qZ29rIn0.AgI-vvm-koCoupjCwZXCGwdYu_D1iw9=
ecHmePkbA3ys ]
=E2=80=94Sam Jennings  in The Metropolitan Review =20
Seth Rogen is dreaming of New Hollywood. Just a few weeks ago, Apple=E2=80=
=99s The Studio won 13 Emmys=E2=80=94setting the record for most wins for a=
 comedy series. The cynical read on this would be that there=E2=80=99s noth=
ing Hollywood loves more than another backstage satire about itself; such a=
n avalanche of golden trophies is as much a marker of the movie business=E2=
=80=99 self-love as it is for any qualities of the show, which are plenty. =
Certainly, The Studio is no Sunset Boulevard=E2=80=94no pitch-black excoria=
tion of the underbelly of the world=E2=80=99s glitziest exploitation land, =
nor some more highly wrought tragic riff on a dying medium. Still, Rogen=E2=
=80=99s show has the distinction of being the first contemporary piece of m=
edia to depict the process behind the movie industry as it is right now=E2=
=80=94and to actually say something about it.
The first of these things that The Studio says, it says quite literally=E2=
=80=94buried in an exchange between soon-to-be-head of the fictional Contin=
ental Studios, Matt Remick (Rogen), and his assistant, Quinn Hackett (Chase=
 Sui Wonders, one of the first great actresses in years who could genuinely=
 play a =E2=80=9930s screwball comedienne). In the first minutes of the fir=
st episode, Remick reveals he has to take meetings with representatives fro=
m both Rubik=E2=80=99s Cube and Jenga. One of the funnier through lines in =
the show is Continental=E2=80=99s desperate attempt to find IP comparable t=
o Barbie, though Remick would rather be making something truly prestigious:
Quinn: Oh my god, this is so depressing. I=E2=80=99m like, 30 years too lat=
e to this fucking industry.
Matt: I know, trust me, if it was up to me, we=E2=80=99d be focusing on mak=
ing the next Rosemary=E2=80=99s Baby or Annie Hall or, you know, some great=
 film that wasn=E2=80=99t directed by a fuckin=E2=80=99 pervert.
Quinn: Turns out perverts make great movies.
Matt: They really do.
It=E2=80=99s chuckle-worthy, and those two titles are really picked more fo=
r their famously loathsome directors than as proper stand-ins for their per=
iod. Yet it=E2=80=99s still clear that what=E2=80=99s on Remick=E2=80=99s m=
ind is the same thing that seems to be on many minds these days: that grand=
 romantic lost world of New Hollywood, the final glory days stretching acro=
ss the late 1960s and =E2=80=9970s, when every year Hollywood seemed to min=
t future classics pitched to actual adult audiences=E2=80=94days when a fil=
m like The Godfather might be considered serious movie art, top the box off=
ice, and still win a bevy of Oscars on top of it all.
In the episode, Remick soon gets his promotion, yet when he walks into a me=
eting with his new boss, intent on selling his idea that prestige and box o=
ffice results ought to be reconciled, he walks out instead with a single bo=
ttom line: making a tentpole film out of Kool-Aid. And so, many antics thro=
ughout later episodes will center around Remick=E2=80=99s attempts to be ta=
ken seriously as a =E2=80=9Cfilmmaker=E2=80=9D while having to hawk superhe=
ro movies, cast IP cash-ins, and avoid being bought by Amazon, fucking over=
 real filmmakers like Martin Scorsese along the way. Dozens of celebrities =
come and go, playing themselves, and the show does a fine job of skewering =
awards shows and Comic-Con reveals, along with the general, ambient sense t=
hat movie studios these days seem to investors like outdated appendages of =
tech companies.
In what=E2=80=99s probably the show=E2=80=99s best episode, =E2=80=9CThe Wa=
r,=E2=80=9D Quinn and her co-executive Sal Saperstein (Ike Barinholtz) sabo=
tage each other=E2=80=99s projects in increasingly spiteful ways. Sal wants=
 to hire the actual director of Smile to make a clear rip-off, called Wink.=
 Quinn wants to bring in Owen Kline=E2=80=94a young director with a single =
small A24 film that went to Cannes, which she pitches to Remick as being =
=E2=80=9Cexecutive produced by the Safdie brothers.=E2=80=9D Of course, the=
 prestige-coveting Remick loves the twinkling sound of the Safdies, A24, an=
d Cannes=E2=80=94but slick old Hollywood Sal declares Wink is for normal pe=
ople, not =E2=80=9Cpansexual mixologists living in Bed-Stuy.=E2=80=9D When =
Sal accidentally destroys a movie set with a poorly lobbed burrito, Quinn o=
penly celebrates how easy it would be to get him fired: =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99=
m technically a bit of a minority. A bit of a woman of color. So you=E2=80=
=99re double fucked. I=E2=80=99m gonna be a hero! There=E2=80=99s gonna be =
marches in my name!=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s a good, healthy sign that a TV sh=
ow can finally make light of these kinds of things.
The Studio gets all its details right, gives us what I imagine is a painful=
ly accurate image of the contemporary foibles and essential vapidity of Hol=
lywood=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s perfectly funny, very well made, sweetly nostal=
gic, and dead-on with its skewering. It=E2=80=99s the kind of thing 10,000 =
critics have surely declared, =E2=80=9CA HILARIOUS HEARTFELT LOVE LETTER TO=
 THE MOVIES.=E2=80=9D And it was surely some murky combo of this sentiment =
and its genuinely pointed satire that managed to bag it so many Emmys. But =
in the end, the thing that the show cannot quite escape is just what haunte=
d it from that first exchange: the glory days of the medium are gone, never=
 to return. Studios are locked in a battle against their own capitalistic d=
ecay; it=E2=80=99s never been harder to get masses of people to sit down fo=
r a film; and the stuff we do make on any big scale has never been stupider=
, or more infantile. O New New Hollywood, where art thou?
